independent_work.et:
I Oral presentation  at the seminar: (maximum 15 minutes): 
Topics:  
1)	Admissibility criteria (European Court of Human Rights);  
2)	Single judge at the European Court of Human Rights;  
3)	Well established case-law (WECL) and three member committees at the European Court of Human Rights;  
4)	Seven judges chambers and their impact to the case law of the European Court of Human Rights. What impacts have the inadmissibility decisions to the case-law?  
5)	Referal and relinbquishment also appeal procedure to the Grand Chamber of the European Court of Human Rights and the Grand Chamber panel;  
6)	(Oral) hearings at the European Court of Human Rights, including Third Party  interventions;  
7)	How is the judgment of the Grand Chamber of the European Court of Human Rights prepared?  
8)	European Court of Human Rights and comperative law research;  
9)	European Court of Human Rights  and European consensus;  
10)	Dissenting opinions at the European Court of Human Rights; 
11)	Inter-state cases at the European Court of Human Rights;    
12)	Subsidiarity versus European Court of Human Rights as a constitutional court in Europe;  
13)	Margin of appreciation in the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;    
14)	European Convention on Human Rights as a living document;  
15)	Social and economic rights in the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
16)	Most important case-law of the European Court of Human Rights on human dignity;  
17)	Right to life and European Court of Human Rights;   
18)	Right to a fair trial (choose one or two aspects only) and the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
19)	Advisory opinions of the European Court of Human Rights and their impact on the Contracting States;  
20)	Freedom of expression versus right to respect private life in the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
21)	Right to liberty and security in the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;    
22)	Prisoners rights and European Court of Human Rights;   
23)	Prohibition of torture and inhuman or degreading treatment in the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
24)	Modern slavery and forced labour and the case law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
25)	Freedom of assembly and association as seen by the European Court of Human Rights - choose one problematic country as an example;  
26)	Ne bis in idem in the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;  
27)	Right to property and European Court of Human Rights;   
28)	No punishment without law as understood by the European Court of Human Rights;    
29)	Right to free elections in the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
30)	Right to an effective remedy in the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
31)	Hate speech and the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;  
32)	Rights of foreigners and the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
33)	Childrens rights and the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
34)	Right of elderly people and the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
35)	 Equal treamtent in the the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
36)	 Freedom of religion and the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;  
37)	Right to education in the case-law of the European Court of Human Rights;   
38)	 Political cases and the European Court of Human Rights; 
39)	Most important cases connected to Russia in the European Court of Human Rights;  
40)	Most important cases connected to Turkey in the European Court of Human Rights;   
41)	Most important cases connected to France in the European Court of Human Rights;  
42)	Most important cases connected to Germany in the European Court of Human Rights;   
43)	Most important cases connected to Italy in the European Court of Human Rights;   
44)	Most important cases connected to Poland in the European Court of Human Rights;   
45)	Most important cases connected to Ukraine in the European Court

grade_preconditions.et:
46)	Most important cases connected to Romania in the European Court of Human Rights;   
47)	European Court of Human Rights and European Union law;   
48)	European Court of Human Rights and critics in academic world and professional literature;  
49)	European Court of Human Rights and COVID-19; 
50)	European Court of Human Rights and Estonian Supreme Court.   

II Choose freely one judgment of the European Court of Human Rights and analyse it by preparing a maximum of 10 power point slides in which you will need to answer to the following questions: who were the parties in this case; in which formation the European Court of Human Rights was sitting and deciding; which human right was in play in the case; did the case bring along any considerable impact/changes to the case-law of the European Court of Human Rigts, to the development of human rights in general; what were the most important aspects of the judgment; what did the Court exactly decide, was there any compensation awarded; how did the state (respondendt government)/states react; were there any comments about this judgment in the literature; has the judgment been implemented/executed? 

Condition to attend teh exam: Oral seminar presentation and a case study;

